 catalogued and reused within the scholarly community. The work of its contributors offers valuable insights into how “the digital” continues to shape the questions medievalists ask and the ways they answer them, but also into how those questions and answers can lead to new tools, approaches, and points of reference within the field of digital humanities itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCivilization, MedievalxComputer network resources. 0aMiddle AgesxComputer network resources. 0aMiddle AgesxStudy and teachingxMethodology. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aDigital Humanities.  aMedieval Studies.  ahistoriographical sources.  apublic engagement.  ascholarship.1 aDavis, Lisa Fagin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorin, Rowan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverhart, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilsdorf, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilsdorf, Sean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIrvine, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcewan, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorreale, Laura K, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorreale, Laura K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTorgerson, J. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908i